Are we confounded by genes that arenâ€™t real?

This notebook compares model residual distributions between gene with symbol annotations and genes without. We have wondered if genes without annotation, which are less likely to be â€œrealâ€ genes, are biasing our downstream analyses.

Functions

This chunk defines a function for loading and preparing residual data.

read_prepare_data <- function(file_pattern, ensembl_symbol_df) {
  
  model_files <- list.files(
    path = model_dir,
    full.names = TRUE,
    pattern = file_pattern
  ) |>
    purrr::set_names(
      \(f) {stringr::str_split_i(basename(f), pattern = "_", i = 1)}
    )
  
  model_files |>
    purrr::map(
      \(model_file) {
        model_data <- readr::read_rds(model_file)
        
        residuals_df <- model_data$data |> 
          dplyr::mutate(residuals = unname(resid(model_data$model))) |> 
          dplyr::left_join(ensembl_symbol_df, by = "ensembl_id") |>
          # If the join resulted in an NA, then it's not annotated
          dplyr::mutate(status = ifelse(
            is.na(gene_symbol), 
            "not_annotated", 
            "annotated"
          ))
    }) |>
    purrr::list_rbind(names_to = "project_id")
}

This chunk defines a function for plotting histograms.

make_histogram <- function(df, xvar, title) {
  ggplot(df) +
    aes(x = {{xvar}}, y = after_stat(ndensity), fill = status) + 
    geom_histogram(position = "identity", alpha = 0.45, bins = 100) +
    facet_grid(rows = vars(project_id)) +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
    ggtitle(title)  
}

This chunk defines a function for modeling and viewing results.

fit_model <- function(df) {
    
  fit <- summary(lm(residuals ~ status * project_id, data = df))
  diff_table <- df |>
    split(df$project_id) |>
    purrr::map(
      \(df_){
      mean(df_$residuals[df_$status == "annotated"]) - mean(df_$residuals[df_$status == "not_annotated"])
    })
  
  return(list(fit, diff_table))
}

This chunk defines a function for calculating the ratio of annotated to unannotated genes per project.

calculate_ratio <- function(df) {
  df |>
    dplyr::select(project_id, ensembl_id, status) |>
    dplyr::distinct() |>
    dplyr::group_by(project_id) |>
    dplyr::count(status) |>
    tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from = status, values_from = n) |>
    dplyr::mutate(ratio = annotated/not_annotated)  
}

Unfiltered data

Weâ€™ll start by exploring this question for residuals whose models included all genes.

unfiltered_df <- read_prepare_data("all-genes\\.rds$", ensembl_symbol_df)

make_histogram(unfiltered_df, residuals, "residual distributions") +
  coord_cartesian(xlim= c(-15, 15))

It appears that the residuals for annotated genes are slightly higher than residuals for genes without annotations. Letâ€™s fit a quick linear model to check how much, and also look at the mean difference among projects directly. One wonders, whatâ€™s the ratio of annotated to not annotated genes for each version of the data (unfiltered and filtered)? The unfiltered should be the same for all projects, but filtered will be different -

calculate_ratio(unfiltered_df)

Ah, well thatâ€™s a nice check for free!

Letâ€™s also make sure these values are consistent with regards to the ensembl/symbol mapping in the first place. We need to only consider genes present in the data here - not all genes in ensembl_symbol_df are present in our data because this map was generated from an ScPCA SCE object. But, since bulk used a slightly different reference during mapping, only genes present in both bulk and pseudobulk went into the models, and hence are in the data we read in here. Therefore, weâ€™ll bring in a third-party bulk-derived file for this check.

# arbitrarily pick project 1 tpm as a spot that has the expected present IDs

  dplyr::pull(ensembl_id)

Looking good!

Now, how did filtering change this ratio?

calculate_ratio(filtered_df)

After filtering, the ratio of annotated:not_annotated goes down. This means we have reduced our share of annotated genes during the filtering, which maybe was not in the spirit of the filtering or suggests that our current filtering strategy may need to shift.
